dparser
Class Message

java.lang.Object
  dparser.Message
Direct Known Subclasses:
Accelerometer, BOverflow, CANMessage, CANOverflow, CTMessage, DismountMessage, SDMessage, SDMount, VoltageMessage, vPerf
public abstract class Message
extends Object

Abstract message class. This is the basis for all messages coming from the datalogger. All messages have an opcode, possibly a timestamp, and maybe a payload. This class handles that ambiguity. It is extended by the various types of message classes to handle the different opCodes.

Since:
2012.05.15
Author:
Derek Chou

Field Detail

timestamped

public boolean timestamped
Does the Message have a timestamp? If it does, this is set to true. Otherwise, this defaults to false.

isCAN

public boolean isCAN
Is the Message a CAN Message? If so, this is set to true. Otherwise, this defaults to false.

hasData

public boolean hasData
Does the Message have data? If so, this is set to true. Otherwise, this defaults to false.

timestamp

protected Double timestamp
This Double is set to whatever the timestamp of the Message is, if there is one. It does NOT contain the timestamp error.
Defaults to null if there is no timestamp.

timestampFrac

protected Integer timestampFrac
While timestamp is a decimal number, timestampFrac is an Integer meant to represent the numerator over 1024. Defaults to null if there is no timestamp error.

tsError

protected Double tsError
This Double is set to whatever the timestamp error of the Message is, if there is one.
Defaults to null if there is no timestamp.

tsErrorFrac

protected Integer tsErrorFrac
While tsError is a decimal number, tsErrorFrac is an Integer meant to represent the numerator over 1024. Defaults to null if there is no timestamp error.

header

protected ArrayList<String> header
All Messages *should* have a header, but this may not be the case. This is intended to be the name that is sorted by the parser in the matrix of data, and the human-readable name of the parameter being parsed.

data

protected ArrayList<String> data
This is analagous to the payload in the datalogger messages.

time

protected Double time
This is the timebase that is currently being used with the datalogger. It is sure to change once the PRM messages are actually of use.

vBase

protected Double vBase
This is the voltbase that is currently being used with the datalogger. It is sure to change once the PRM messages are actually of use.

Constructor Detail

Message

public Message(String[] info,
               boolean ts)
Sets up a new Message. The constructor first determines whether there is a timestamp associated with the Message, and then acts accordingly.

Parameters:
info - The split String coming from the datalogger line. Element 0 should be an opCode. Element 1 should either be a timestamp, or the payload that should be processed accordingly. Element 2, if it exists, will be part of the payload.
ts - True means that there is a timestamp. False means that there is no timestamp.

params

public String[] params()
Returns:
An array of Strings that includes the Message's timestamp (if it exists), the error on the timestamp (if it exists), the header, and the data carried by the Message (if it exists).

pack

public ArrayList<String> pack()
                       throws PackException
Intended only for use with timestamped Messages going to Motor team.

Returns:
The major parameters of a Message timestamp, header, and data in that order. This is for the Matlab reader - the format will be as follows:
timestamp;name;description;data
Throws:
PackException

toString

public String toString()
Prints out the Message and its timestamp and its error. If the timestamp and/or error do not exist, they will not be printed.
